solutions.content:
# Shift 2D Grid
The problem at hand requires us to shift a 2D grid to the right cyclically k times. It is the equivalent of applying right shift operation k times.
One right shift operation does the following:
(i,j) becomes (i, j+1)
if j == n-1, then it becomes (i+1, 0)
if j == n-1 and i == m-1, then it becomes (0, 0)

## Approach 1 Calculate Indices for each element
In this approach, we make a copy of the entire matrix, and then fill it with the corresponding elements according to the shifted coordinates.
```
pair<int, int> shift(int i, int j, int k) {
	j+=k;
	if(j >= n) {
		i += j/n;
		j = j%n;
	}
	if(i >= m) {
		i = i%m;
	}
	return {i,j};
}
```
The above function gives the shifted coordinates given the original coordinates and the shifted amount. We could call this function at every (i,j) in the matrix and fill the corresponding place.

But this approach would be slow, as we would have to make O(m*n) calls just to this function.
A better way to do this is to just call it once for the starting point, and then keep right shifting once for every subsequent element.

```
nj++;
if(nj == n) {
	ni++;
	nj = 0;
}
if(ni == m) {
	ni = 0;
}
```

This code calculates the next position given the new position of the previous point (ni, nj)

So the full code for this approach is as follows:
### Code (C++)
```
class Solution {
    int m, n;
    pair<int, int> shift(int i, int j, int k) {
        j+=k;
        if(j >= n) {
            i += j/n;
            j = j%n;
        }
        if(i >= m) {
            i = i%m;
        }
        return {i,j};
    }
public:
    vector<vector<int>> shiftGrid(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {
        m = grid.size(), n = grid[0].size();
        vector<vector<int>> newGrid(m, vector<int>(n));
        auto [ni, nj] = shift(0, 0, k);
        for(int i = 0; i<m; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j<n; j++) {
                newGrid[ni][nj] = grid[i][j];
                nj++;
                if(nj == n) {
                    ni++;
                    nj = 0;
                }
                if(ni == m) {
                    ni = 0;
                }
            }
        }
        return newGrid;
    }
};
```

### Complexity
**Time Complexity:** O(m * n)
**Space Complexity:** O(m * n) (for returning the new matrix)

## Approach 2: Treat Matrix as Array and Right Shift k Times
We already have a good approach for right shifting an array k times;
```
reverse(arr, 0, n-1);
reverse(arr, 0, k-1);
reverse(arr, k, n-1);
```
If we can treat the whole matrix as a flat array, we can apply the same algorithm and solve this question very easily.
To do this, we can't use the normal reverse function, as it warrants flattening the matrix, which we actually don't need. We just need to *pretend* that the matrix is flattened..
This is accomplished by taking the array coordinates and mapping them to row and column indices underneath.
```
void reverse(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int l, int r) {
	while(l<r) {
		int lr = l/n, lc = l%n;
		int rr = r/n, rc = r%n;
		if(rr == m) rr = 0;
		swap(grid[lr][lc], grid[rr][rc]);
		l++;
		r--;
	}
}
```
Once this modification is made, the whole problem reduces to just three more statements
```
reverse(grid, 0, m*n-1);
reverse(grid, 0, k-1);
reverse(grid, k, m*n-1);
```

### Code (C++) 
```
class Solution {
    int m, n;
    void reverse(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int l, int r) {
        while(l<r) {
            int lr = l/n, lc = l%n;
            int rr = r/n, rc = r%n;
            if(rr == m) rr = 0;
            swap(grid[lr][lc], grid[rr][rc]);
            l++;
            r--;
        }
    }
public:
    vector<vector<int>> shiftGrid(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {
        m = grid.size(), n = grid[0].size();
        k = k%(m*n);
        if(k == 0) return grid;
        reverse(grid, 0, m*n-1);
        reverse(grid, 0, k-1);
        reverse(grid, k, m*n-1);
        return grid;
    }
};
```

### Caution!
This code modifies the input matrix itself.
I regard this as a *hacky* way of achieving O(1) extra space, since one is bound to require some space for storing the output of the program. Plus this approach can lead to loss of information if implemented incorrectly. So take care while using it, or just make a copy of the input matrix and apply this algorithm on it instead.

### Complexity
**Time Complexity:** O(m * n)
**Space Complexity:** O(1) (see above Caution)


