solutions.content:
To solve this question we required two observations.
**Observation 1:-** If k is linear multiple of row(r in code) and column(c in code) than we get initial grid after shifting.Means answer after k shift=answer after k%(r*c).
**Observation 2:-**  At every n * c shifting(linear multiple of length of column) , we are shifting  whole row with other row.

After these two observations only column shifting is remain.
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> shiftGrid(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {
        //for number of raw
        int r=grid.size();

        //for number of column
        int c=grid[0].size();

        //to make the copy of the grid
        vector<vector<int>>ans=grid;

        k=k%(r*c);//by observation 1

        //to calculate the number of row shift required.
        int r_shift=k/c;

        //to calculate the total column shift required .
        int c_shift=k%c;

        for(int i=0;i<r;i++)
        {
            grid[(i+r_shift)%r]=ans[i];//row shift by observation 2.
        }

        ans=grid;

        for(int i=0;i<r;i++)
        {
            for(int j=0;j<c;j++)
            {
                grid[(i+(j+c_shift)/c)%r][(j+c_shift)%c]=ans[i][j];//coloumn shift.
            }
        }
        return grid;
    }
};
//If you like my approach than plz upvote me.
```

