# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We don't need to compute the values at all, given the formula we can trace back if, at each level in the tree, we have to go through the left or right subtree.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Given the formula, we know that odd values are in left subtree w.r.t. their parent, even values to the right.

Reworking the formula backward, we can derive the immediate predecessor in the path from root to target (e.g., (value - 1) / 2 for odd values, (value - 2) / 2 for even), in this way we can compute an array with the path root (index 0) to the target value (index equivalent to the depth at which the value lies).

With this array, we can, at each step, decide if we need to go left (odd value), or right (even value), and we just need to follow the right child of the tree.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(log N) for computing the target level, O(log N) for computing the array, O(log N) to traverse, still summing up to O(log N) in total.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The array for each requests is as long as the path, which is O(log N).

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class FindElements {

    TreeNode root;

    public FindElements(TreeNode root) {
        this.root = root;
        root.val = 0;
    }

    public boolean find(int target) {
        if (root == null) {
            return false;
        }
        if (target == 0 && root != null) {
            return true;
        }

        // here we derive the depth where the target element is, knowing that 2^i elements are at level i
        int targetLevel = 0;
        for (int tot = 1; ; targetLevel++) {
            int left = tot - 1;
            int right = tot * 2 - 2;
            if (target >= left && target <= right) {
                break;
            }
            tot *= 2;
        }

        // now we compute the path backwards with the reverse of the given formula
        int[] path = new int[targetLevel + 1];
        path[targetLevel] = target;
        for (int i = targetLevel - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            path[i] = (path[i + 1] - (path[i + 1] % 2 != 0 ? 1 : 2)) / 2;
        }

        // here we traverse the tree, guided by the array
        TreeNode curr = root;
        for (int i = 1; curr != null && i < path.length; i++) {
            boolean left = path[i] % 2 != 0;
            curr = left ? curr.left : curr.right;
        }
        // at the final step, we just need to check that the node is there, if it is, it's our target
        return curr != null;
    }
}

/**
 * Your FindElements object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * FindElements obj = new FindElements(root);
 * boolean param_1 = obj.find(target);
 */
```

