# Intuition & Approach
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
***There are two approaches in which this can be solved.***

- We can avoid 'Recover' of the tree. But everytime we want to Find a value, we would need to traverse the contaminated tree via BFS to find possibility of existance of the target element.
- We can recover the contaminated tree and everytime we recover a node, we'll add it's value to a HashSet. With this the Find can work in O(1).
-*<b>If we wish not to use a HashSet, then we can "Find" via BFS efficiently compared to DFS</b>. Because, since the elements will be ordered at each level (top-to-bottom + left-to-right), we can conclude that the target element is not present if we encounter any element whose value is greater than our target. The same cannot be concluded via DFS.*

![Screenshot 2023-06-19 084844.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/28d70aee-77ce-4759-9af4-fb451bcf67ad_1687144782.9810998.png)


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N) - Recover - as we need to visit every node of the contaminated tree.
O(1) - Find

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N) - as we use a HashSet
*if we wish not use a hashset, we can search via DFS with O(1) space complexity and O(N) runtime complexity*

