# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
->To implement this, I chose to use a depth-first traversal of the binary tree. Starting from the root node, I assign the value 0 to the root and recursively recover the values of the left and right subtrees based on the parent node's value.

->During the recovery process, I store the recovered values in an unordered set (values) to enable efficient lookup in the find method.

->The expression values.count(target) > 0 compares the result of values.count(target) with 0. If the count is greater than 0, it means that the target value was found in the set, which gives us true. Otherwise, if the count is 0, it means that the target value is not present in the set, and we can return false.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
DFS and Unordered_set

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N)
