solutions.content:
Two BFS. 
1st BFS to push box as regular BFS. 
*2nd BFS to check if the person can reach the box inside 1st BFS

BFS to push box. For each positon of box, check if player can push it.
Box can be pushed only when it has two opposite adajacent grids are empty
	1. traverse the grid to find the location of player, box, target, and set their grid value to '.'
	2. Use 4d boolean array visited (boolean[box_x][box_y][player_x][player_y]) to record visited box
	3. In the BFS Queue, it is an array of box_x, box_y, player_x, player_y, step
	4. During BFS, check the 2 adajcent grids for the box in x and y direction. 
If both they are within grid and have '.', do second BFS to see if the player can reach the position 

Time complexity: O(n^2*m^2)
Space complexity: O(n*m)
n, m is the grid width and length

```
class Solution {
    public int minPushBox(char[][] grid) {
        int m = grid.length;
        int n = grid[0].length;
        int[] box = {-1, -1};
        int[] player = {-1, -1};
        int[] target = {-1, -1};
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (grid[i][j] == 'S') {
                    player = new int[]{i, j};
                } else if (grid[i][j] == 'B') {
                    box = new int[]{i, j};
                } else if (grid[i][j] == 'T') {
                    target = new int[]{i, j};
                }
            }
        }
        grid[player[0]][player[1]] = '.';
        grid[box[0]][box[1]] = '.';
        grid[target[0]][target[1]] = '.';
        boolean[][][][] visited = new boolean[m][n][m][n];
        Queue<int[]> queue = new ArrayDeque<>();
        queue.offer(new int[]{box[0], box[1], player[0], player[1], 0});
        visited[box[0]][box[1]][player[0]][player[1]] = true;
